abstract = {The gig economy's disruptions on incumbent businesses have raised significant attention from policy-makers. This research focuses on one of the gig economy platforms, the online peer-to-peer (P2P) short-term rental (STR) platform. We examine how the governmental STR interventions affect the long-term rental (LTR) market. Using the prospect theory and the theory in the economics of regulation, we study the relationship between the STR regulations and the LTR rental prices. We find a nonlinear relationship between the STR regulation and the LTR rental prices through analyzing a constructed panel of monthly LTR and STR data from 15 cities across the United States. The nonlinear relationship between these two indicates that STR regulations only have a short-term impact on the LTR market prices but they cannot effectively contain the negative impacts of STR on the LTR market in the long run. Thus, policy-makers need to find alternative ways to govern the STR businesses. We discussed the related practical implications for gig economy research and policy-making.}
}
